The team of Czech and German scientists provides evidence of new compounds capable of moderateing the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some available medicines already.
AIDS cannot be cured so far.
However, the life of patients can be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If replication of the virus is not completely eliminated, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, medicines no longer work.
The work of the three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
It was shown that the substances called metal carborans have an effect on the albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metal carborans are compounds of copper, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that is different from all medicines used today, so they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘better’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalcarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyetheric cages composed of the atoms of steel, hydrogen and carbon are joined by the atom of metal, in this case by cobalt.
