Couples who violate politics face huge fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and labor discrimination.
Chinese officials have made good use of the policy for their contribution to avoid critical pressure on their natural resources, while human rights defenders have reported abuses in the imposition of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have had abortions according to the sex of the fetus, leading to a high unnatural male-female ratio.
In recent years, demographic officials have gradually abandoned their position on the policy of a single child.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife are single children, and in 2007 many of their hardline slogans were eased.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor of the Institute for Demographic Research at the University of Beijing, said that central government officials have recently been discussing even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost evening in the morning, the posters that ordered families to have one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be ideal for having a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family and volunteer planning officers to visit couples in their homes and slide leaflets under the doors.
It has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officers say the response has been very little overwhelming.
Disabling Response
Although officials of a rural city outside Shanghai argue that they observed a moderate increase in the requests of couples who wanted a second child after the campaign was launched, the most urban districts did not indicate any change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications a month.
The disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to reach only about 165,000, slightly higher than in 2009, but less than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Caolu Municipal Family Planning Committee in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason many people do not want any more children.
They want to give their first son the best, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 years old, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally enabled to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have insufficient medical and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection network, they maintain, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West wrongly view single child policy as a question of rights, Yang said, an engineer of construction whose wife is pregnant for seven months from the first child of the couple.
Yeah, we're stealing the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the human resources manager, said he wanted a single child because she was also: "We were the center of our families and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42-year-old owner of a translation agency, explained it more thoroughly.
For parents with two middle-class races, which reduce the birth rate, he said, it is to be successful enough as to be selfish.
People between the ages of 20 and 30 grew up seeing their parents struggle during the first days of the Chinese experiment with capitalism and did not want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even one child takes a long time from parents, he did.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space issues, "they have to remodel their apartment", and the strategic "have to have a curriculum prepared for the best custody when the child has 9 months."
Most of your friends are willing to face this once, Chen said, but not two.
Ours is the first generation with the highest standard of living, he manifested.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
A United Nations group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN climate conference, characterized so far by challenging positions and mutual re-criminations, caught renewed attention on Friday with the disclosure of a document that provides for ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important advance in a timeless negotiation, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Drafted by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not mention how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their carbon production, and what would be the limit of the global increase in temperature that political strategies would be willing to tolerate.
This gives you a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequitt, High Representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page paper, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official Yvo de Boer described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 between 25 and 45 per cent, compared with 1990 levels, while the main developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period between 15 and 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged talks on Friday, promising to provide $3,600 million annually over the next three years, to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday presented the same kind of verbal artificial fires that dominated the conversations last week.
The United States' special climate mission, Todd Stern, rejected claims requesting mandatory cut-offs of greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The manobra indicated that Obama was adopting a tougher line with China with regard to what the Bush administration officials had done just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments one hour after the Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the United States' largest climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" because he had said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically cope with global warming.
With the future economic path of the world's major power at stake, the lines of failure have erupted both within the world on the way of development, as between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said it was not surprising that the main powers were discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even when vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in seeking to contain the major issuers responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change adviser in Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants said that the talks would produce a political agreement at the top.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drew up a preliminary proposal for a 24-page treaty early Friday morning.
Arthur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and require the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency while delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues had to be resolved before the heads of government came to a close.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister, came down from the planes and ran to the halls of the Bella Center, to meetings at closed doors and press conferences, in order to be able to delimit the advertisements that will be held during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where 13,000 people come in and out of the convention centre every day, the activists who touch the guitar present night shows blaring from the countries they believe are being sold, and preliminary hand-to-hand proposals instead of via e-mail) poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, Vice-President of the Global Conservation Policy.
Heavy weights are coming.
